) VALUES (
  (SELECT id FROM auth.users LIMIT 1),
  'Habits Are the Product',
  'habits-are-the-product',
  'Most parenting tools chase outcomes. I care about helping children get good at improving habits. If they master the process of showing up, adjusting, and repeating, outcomes follow without pressure.',
  E'Most parenting tools chase outcomes.\nRead more. Behave better. Hit milestones faster.\n\nI care about none of those directly.\n\nMy mission as a parent is to help my children get good at improving habits. If they master the process of showing up, adjusting, and repeating, outcomes follow without pressure.\n\nHabits compound. Outcomes expire.\n\n## Why I Stopped Focusing on Goals\n\nGoals feel productive. They are easy to talk about. They give adults a sense of control.\n\nThey fail kids.\n\nA goal lives in the future. A habit lives today.\n\nEvery NFL team wants to win a championship. Only teams with disciplined daily habits ever do. Practice routines. Film study. Recovery. Small execution details, repeated relentlessly.\n\nParenting works the same way.\n\nYou do not raise strong readers by talking about reading levels.\nYou raise them by reading every day, even when it feels pointless.\n\n## Habits Are a Parent Skill First\n\nThis system is designed for parents, not children.\n\nKids do not need motivation speeches. They need models. If you want your child to wash their hands when they get home, you wash your hands when you get home. Same time. Same place. Same rule.\n\nThis is why habits must be shared.\n\nParent and child complete the same habit.\nParent and child earn the same coins.\n\nYou lead by doing, not by reminding.\n\n## Why Consistency Matters More Than the Habit Itself\n\nThe topic barely matters.\n\nReading. Manners. Responsibility. Accountability.\nAll are interchangeable early on.\n\nWhat matters is tracking something and doing it again tomorrow.\n\nConsistency builds identity. Identity builds behavior.\n\nA child who sees progress daily learns one thing. Improvement is normal.\n\n## Where Parents Break Down\n\nParents do not lack intention. They lack energy.\n\nMost days feel like survival. Work. Cleanup. Bedtime negotiations. When parents run out of energy, habit leadership disappears.\n\nScreens fill the gap because they are easy.\n\nThis system exists for low-energy days.\n\nOpening the app counts.\nLooking at habits counts.\nCompleting one small action counts.\n\nMomentum beats motivation.\n\n## Repetition Is the Real Win\n\nRepetition is the system.\n\nNo long explanations. No complex setup. Just open, check, do.\n\nThe smallest action still reinforces identity.\n\"I am someone who shows up.\"\n\nMissing days happens. Stopping is the failure.\n\n## How Bad Days Still Work\n\nOn bad days, parents default to screens. This creates an alternative.\n\nHabits replace screen time as the first response.\nScreen time becomes something earned.\n\nCoins remove arguments.\nStructure replaces negotiation.\n\nParents conserve energy. Kids stay engaged.\n\n## What I Want Parents to Realize\n\nChildren reflect us.\n\nTheir consistency mirrors our consistency. Their habits mirror ours.\n\nThis system is not about fixing kids. It is about giving parents a simple way to lead by example, even when exhausted.\n\nShow up first. Let kids follow.\n\n## A Belief I Reject\n\nGoals do not create habits.\n\nDaily action does.\n\nOne day at a time.\nReflect often.\nNever stop.\n\nWithout willingness to adjust behavior, tools do nothing.\n\n## A Small Daily Habit That Works\n\nEvery morning starts the same way.\n\nShe hangs her pajamas on her bed.\n\nNo reward speech. No praise spiral. Just repetition.\n\nIt teaches responsibility.\nIt teaches order.\nIt teaches follow-through.\n\nMore importantly, it teaches consistency.\n\n## This Is the Point\n\nHabits are not a feature.\nThey are the foundation.\n\nBuild the habit.\nRepeat the habit.\nLet outcomes show up later.\n\nThat is how real progress happens.',
  'published',
  ARRAY['parenting', 'habits', 'philosophy'],
  now()
);